The Economy of Violence
COPENHAGEN – What is the greatest source of violence in our world?
Brutal conflicts in Syria, in Ukraine, and elsewhere are constantly in the news, and thus many would probably say war.
But this turns out to be a great mistake.
The correct answer plays a role when we want to find cost-effective solutions for this and other global problems.
It is self-evident that everyone would like to end every war and violence, just as we would like to end poverty, hunger, and climate change, and provide all people access to education.
However, given limited resources, there are limits to what the international community can do.
We must set priorities and for that, one can use an economic cost-benefit analysis.
The international community is working on new development goals for the next 15 years and the Copenhagen Consensus has asked some of the leading economists in the world to evaluate which goals, in their view, would be the smartest.
Is the goal to reduce violence worth the investment of funds that could otherwise be spent, for example, on combating hunger?
And if so, which forms of violence should be targeted?
A study by James Fearon from Stanford University and Anke Höffler from the Center for the Study of African Economies at Oxford University indicates that social violence – murders and especially violence against women and children – poses a much greater problem than civil wars.
For every death on the battlefield of a civil war, nine people die due to interpersonal violence, and for every two combatants who die, one child is killed.
In 2008, 418,000 people were killed worldwide, and too many countries record murder rates of more than 10 deaths per 100,000 inhabitants, which the World Health Organization classifies as an epidemic.
A single murder in America costs society 9.1 million US dollars.
Gemessen am Nationalkommen weltweit kostet allein diese Form von Gewaltverbrechen 1,7% des globalen Bruttosozialprodukts (BIP).
Natürlich handelt es sich dabei nicht um einen direkten finanziellen Verlust für die Weltwirtschaft, sondern um eine Art und Weise, die Folgen zum Ausdruck zu bringen.
Wenn Morde abgeschafft werden könnten, wären Gesellschaften auf aller Welt in einer Weise besser gestellt, die sich mit 1,7% des BIP beziffern lässt.
Vergleichen wir dies mit den deutlich geringen Kosten von Bürgerkriegen, die rund 0,2% des weltweiten BIP entsprechen.
Das ist allerdings immer noch viel weniger als die größte Quelle von Gewalt überhaupt: häusliche Gewalt gegen Frauen.
Based on studies published in the scientific journal Science, 28% of all women in sub-Saharan Africa experienced violence from their partners or family members last year.
This includes women who were beaten, married off at a young age, subjected to sexual violence, victims of crimes in the name of "honor," and female genital mutilation.
According to a cautious estimate, the societal costs of violence by intimate partners alone amount to 4.4 trillion US dollars or 5.2% of the global GDP.
The second largest source of violence is the mistreatment of children, which is carried out in 80% of cases by parents.
The definition of what constitutes child abuse varies from culture to culture, but roughly 15% of children experience what the UN calls severe physical punishment each month.
Hierzu zählen Schläge ins Gesicht, an den Kopf oder auf die Ohren, und ein Viertel dieser Kinder wird wiederholt und so heftig wie möglich mit einem Gegenstand geschlagen.
Jeden Monat ergeht dieses Leid über rund 290 Millionen Kinder.
Die sozialen Kosten belaufen sich auf 3,6 Billionen US-Dollar oder 4,2% des globalen BIP.
Ein winziger Bruchteil der internationalen Hilfsgelder fließt derzeit in die Verringerung von Gewalt in der Gesellschaft und in die Verbesserung von Strafrechtssystemen.
Die enormen Kosten, die von der Gesellschaft und von Einzelnen getragen werden, schreien förmlich danach, etwas zu unternehmen.
Unfortunately, there are still few reliable insights into where limited resources could be used most effectively.
All that can be said is that the money spent on reducing violence could be used more precisely.
Large sums of aid are allocated to "fragile states" to help end or prevent civil wars, yet only 0.27% of international aid goes to projects with the component of "crime prevention."
Other programs can contribute indirectly, but clearly much could be improved.
Some solutions, it is clear, work very well.
Stronger social institutions can reduce violence against children.
Studies in the US state of Washington have shown that home visits by trained personnel can reduce child abuse, improve the quality of life for children, and enhance their physical and mental health, while also reducing the costs of care and proceedings.
Every dollar spent on this program yields a benefit of $14: It is thus an extremely cost-effective measure.
In many cases, societal attitudes need to change.
To reduce violence against women and girls, a program in Uganda called SASA! works towards this goal.
(Swahili for "Now!") for spreading the idea that violence in relationships is unacceptable and contributed to halving the number of cases.
This is a fantastic result, even though no analysis of cost-effectiveness is available.
There are examples from other countries where effective measures have been taken.
In 1993, there were 80 murders per 100,000 inhabitants in Bogotá.
With a comprehensive approach – a time limit for alcohol sales, reclaiming public space, and improvements in police and justice systems – the murder rate was reduced to 21 victims per 100,000 inhabitants in 2004.
This is still a high number, but far below the murder rate of 55 victims per 100,000 inhabitants in Detroit.
Alcohol plays a role in many physical attacks, and the findings from Bogotá suggest that controlling its availability could be of significant importance.
In the United Kingdom, a pilot study on better enforcing existing regulations showed that physical attacks could be reduced in a very cost-efficient manner, with the benefits outweighing the costs by a ratio of 17 to 1.
We may not know enough yet, but two points are clear: First, domestic violence against women and children incurs societal costs of 8 trillion US dollars per year and thus represents a huge – and largely ignored – global problem.
Second, there are solutions that can address some of these issues in a very cost-effective manner.
Aus diesem Grund gehört die Verringerung häuslicher Gewalt in die engere Auswahl für die nächsten Entwicklungsziele der Welt.
